<HEAD>
<TITLE>Federalism - Issues 96 - Heritage</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/heritage/paperh.jpg">
<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 14</h3>
<center><h2>FEDERALISM </H2>


<B><CITE>By Douglas Seay and Wesley Smith </CITE></B>
<P>
<A HREF="chpt14.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt14.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt14.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt14.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A>
<p></CENTER>

<p><a href="chpt14text.html">Additional Text</a><p>


<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>With frustrated Americans focusing their anger increasingly  on Washington
and gridlock, many political candidates in 1994  successfully ran against
Washington, appealing to voters to &quot;throw  the bums out&quot; and replace
them with individuals who are more  honest and more devoted to the public
welfare.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>One result has been that ideas such as devolution and  federalism, ignored
for decades, are back in the forefront of public  debate. Because Washington is
seen as cumbersome, rigid, and  distant from the people, this Congress has
attempted to give the states  and local governments more autonomy and
responsibility in areas  such as welfare. The assumption is that this will
result in greater  experimentation, increased efficiency, and government that
once again  is closer to the people.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Contract With America emphasized the need for  devolution and a shift of
selected responsibilities from Washington to  state and local governments.
However, although devolution in its  many forms may produce benefits in selected
programs, by itself it  will not address the root cause of the many problems
plaguing  American society. The reason: The source of the problem is not an 
inefficient distribution of functions between the different layers of  gov
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 -->  ernment, to be corrected by
reshuffling. Nor is it bad people  holding public office, or even poorly
designed programs. The  fundamental problem is systemic: The Constitutional
system  established by the Framers has been largely dismantled, releasing 
government, especially the national government, from virtually all  restraint.
Unconstrained government inevitably has swept aside civil  society, replacing it
with political decisionmaking and  bureaucratic administration unaccountable to
the public. Together, these  have created the conditions within which the
economic and social  problems now burdening society have arisen and flourished. 
Encroachment by Washington also has blocked state and local  governments, as
well as civil society, from initiating innovative responses  to those problems.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This has resulted in four dilemmas, all of which require action:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>First,</B> the central purpose of the Constitution  limiting the  power
of government  has been forgotten, and many of the  mechanisms for enforcing
those limits have been dismantled.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Second,</B> the states  the key element in the American  constitutional
system  have been stripped of the ability to carry out  their constitutional
responsibility of checking and balancing the  national government, and this has
allowed Washington to assume an  unlimited and unchallengeable role in the
economy, in society, and  in the lives of individuals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Third,</B> the resulting centralization of power in Washington and  the
unchecked expansion of its reach have undermined the  institutions of civil
society and thereby severely weakened the ability of  the people to exercise
self-government. Washington has replaced  civil 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->  society with bureaucratic
rulemaking and administration  from above, and<B> </B>has<B> </B>made
decisionmaking in all areas of public  and private life more responsive to
political factors  and<B> </B>ideologies than to empirical results and the
preferences of the citizenry. In  addition, centralization has insulated
decisionmaking from  participation by the very people most directly affected by
government  programs.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Fourth,</B> the federal judiciary has permitted, even mandated,  an
open-ended expansion of power by the national government,  arrogating to itself
the role of legislature of last resort and imposing  a liberal agenda explicitly
and repeatedly rejected by the electorate.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The national government's rise to dominance has taken  many years. Some
steps, such as the popular election of Senators,  occurred for entirely
democratic reasons and with full public  support; others, such as the weakening
of the criminal justice system,  were accomplished by sleight of hand and
against solid public  opposition. Taken together, they constitute a virtual
rewriting of the  Constitution, the impact of which has yet to be fully
appreciated.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>What the Framers Intended</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A fundamental assumption of the Framers of the Constitution  was that the
American people were and would continue to be  largely self-governing, running
their own affairs by means of the  network of social relationships and voluntary
organizations  collectively known as civil society, such as families,
communities,  and churches. Government, especially local government  controlled

<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 -->  directly by the community, was
seen as a necessary ally of  civil society. But it was restricted to those
limited functions which  civil society could not easily perform for itself, such
as defense,  the police, and the coining of money. The purpose of government 
was to secure an environment within which free people would  control their own
affairs: in other words, an environment that makes  possible the individual &quot;pursuit
of happiness.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P>In writing the Constitution, the Framers had two objectives:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>1)  To correct the failings of the Articles of Confederation,  due
largely to the states' domination of a weak national  government.</B> Thus, a
new national government was created with sufficient  powers to carry out a
limited number of crucial functions, such as  the regulation of international
and interstate commerce, and to  prevent the states from interfering in these
areas.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>2)  To limit the power of the new national government.</B>  Having
fought a revolution against what they defined as tyranny   the unchecked
exercise of power, regardless of motive  their  second, and far more important,
objective was to prevent its  reemergence from their own handiwork. They
therefore spent the bulk of  their deliberations on devising ways to limit the
power of the  national government.
</P>
<P>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>Trusting neither the written word of the Constitution nor  self-restraint on
the part of officeholders to enforce the necessary  limits, the Framers devised
a complex system of checks and balances  in which various political actors were
placed deliberately in  permanent opposition to one another. This tension was
intended to  ensure that the energies and ambitions of the respective  groups 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  would be directed against one
another, thereby protecting  civil society from unwanted interference. The best
known of these  safeguards  the division of the national government into three 
competing branches: executive, legislative, and judicial  has  proven both
effective and durable despite two centuries of change.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Central Role of Federalism</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Even more essential to the intent of the Constitution were the  several
checks and balances between the national government and  the states, and the
division of power between them, a wholly new  system which came to be called
federalism. Despite the crucial  role assigned to it, however, federalism
remains widely misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Federalism is commonly defined as the division of powers  among the federal,
state, and local governments according to which  performs them best. For
example, the national government has  general responsibility for defense; the
states, for most prisons  and roads; and local governments, for schools. Certain
powers, such  as taxation and the regulation of commerce, are shared. Advocates 
of federalism often assert that this division of powers is more  efficient than
centralizing all functions in Washington, and that  innovative approaches to
problems are more likely to emerge from  the experiments of 50 state governments
than from a monolithic  national bureaucracy. In addition, proponents generally 
emphasize the need to keep government as close to the people as possible  by
keeping its functions at the lowest possible level.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>However, all of these arguments in favor of federalism are  subsidiary to
its central purpose: limiting the power of government at  all levels. The
national and state governments were intended to  con
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 -->  strain one another, not to work
hand-in-glove or parcel out  functions to that level of government which will
perform them  best. Thus, the new government was given the power to prevent  the
states from abusing their authority through such actions as  erecting trade
barriers against one another, and national legislation  was given preeminence
over state and local law in those limited  areas reserved to the national
government. In turn, the states were  expected to constrain Washington, as they
were regarded as the  only effective means of doing so.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>So crucial was the role of the states in limiting the  national government's
power that the Framers provided them with  several safeguards, including:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     A direct role</B> in the making of all laws and the
appointment of  all federal officials, including federal judges, through a
Senate  composed of members appointed by the states;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     The ability to block</B> all constitutional amendments proposed 
by Congress and to bypass an out-of-touch national government  altogether by
means of a constitutional convention; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     A written guarantee</B> against Washington's assumption of 
additional powers in the form of the blunt and sweeping language  of the Tenth
Amendment, which reserved all powers not delegated  to the national government
by the Constitution either to the states  or to the people.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>How the Safeguards Were Dismantled</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This carefully constructed system remained largely intact for  over 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 -->  100 years; but beginning in the
early part of this century, the  ability of the states to perform their
constitutional role of limiting  the national government has been progressively
reduced to the  point that it has been virtually eliminated.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The process was a lengthy and complex one, but its principal  landmarks
were:
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     The ratification in 1913 of the 16th and 17th
Amendments,</B>  which removed key restraints on the national government by
giving  it unlimited taxing authority and by mandating that Senators were  to be
elected by popular vote rather than selected by state  legislatures. As a
result, Washington secured the resources necessary  for an open-ended expansion
of its functions even as the states  were removed from the making of national
policy and eliminated as  the principal bulwark against expansion by the
national government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     The national emergencies of the Depression, World War II,  and the
Cold War,</B> which legitimized political forces arguing  for greater power at
the national level to deal with domestic and  international problems. The powers
and functions assumed by  Washington in times of emergency have remained long
after their  original justification has passed. In fact, many of the emergency 
powers of the 1930s were vastly expanded in the 1960s and 1970s in  such
programs as the Great Society and the War on Poverty, each  of which further
increased Washington's power by giving it an  activist leading role in areas of
the economy and society never  before assumed by any level of government.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Beginning in 1937, the Supreme Court's abandonment of its 
traditional role of enforcing limits</B> laid out in the Constitution through  a
series of decisions that have removed virtually all  constitutional 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 -->  restraints on the national
government. The power of the  national government to regulate interstate
commerce, for example, has  been interpreted as being virtually unlimited,
extending to virtually  every area of the economy and society; the Tenth
Amendment,  in effect, has been gutted.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Beginning in the 1950s, in pursuit of what its advocates  have
called a &quot;judicial revolution,&quot;</B> the Supreme Court's radical 
alteration of established interpretations of rights guaranteed by  the
Constitution, with some vastly expanded, others restricted,  and still others
simply invented. This judicial activism has  transformed the Court into an
unelected &quot;super legislature,&quot; effectively  unbound by any restraints.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Judicial Activism</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Judicial activism now extends to all areas of public and private  life
because the Supreme Court and the federal judiciary have  succeeded in granting
themselves virtually unlimited power.  Federal, state, and local laws, duly
enacted by elected officials, have  been struck down; state and local government
functions such as  schools and prisons have been taken over by the federal
courts and  subjected to their increasingly minute direction; and state 
constitutions have been rewritten at will. Referenda passed with  overwhelming
public support are annulled. The courts even order that taxes  be imposed
directly on populations deemed incompetent to  govern themselves.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The courts have engaged in highly subjective and selective  interpretations
of the Constitution, creating rights by locating them  in previously unnoticed &quot;penumbras&quot;
and &quot;invisible radiations&quot;  even 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  as they ignore other, clearly
expressed constitutional  provisions. This has led to inconsistent and confusing
judicial decisions  with little, if any, basis in the Constitution, or even in
common sense.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>-     The First Amendment's guarantee of &quot;speech&quot;</B>
has been  interpreted to include aggressive panhandling, while the provision 
that Congress &quot;shall make no law respecting an establishment of  religion&quot;
has been interpreted to mean that the Ten  Commandments may not be used in
classrooms but that prisoners demanding  pornography must be accommodated.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#1">1</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     The Second Amendment</B> is regularly circumscribed with the 
permission of the federal courts despite the fact that it states  explicitly
that &quot;the right of the people to keep and bear Arms, shall not  be
infringed.&quot;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     The language of the Tenth Amendment,</B> which states with 
magnificent clarity that &quot;the powers not delegated to the United States  by
the Constitution...are reserved to the States respectively, or to  the people,&quot;
has been dismissed as a mere &quot;truism&quot; with no real  application to the
national government's authority.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>In short, unelected, unrepresentative, and ideologically  driven courts have
dispensed with democratic choice and  constitutional procedure to impose
sweeping changes in the law. Intended as  a clear and agreed-upon set of rules,
the Constitution has become  a document subject to the most arbitrary revision
by the  federal courts.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Thus, the system established by the Framers has largely ceased  to exist. Of
the elaborate restraints they placed on the national  gov
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  ernment, virtually none remain
other than those that  Washington chooses to impose on itself. This is not a
subjective judgment:  In recent questioning before the Supreme Court, the
Solicitor  General of the United States was asked to name just one area that
could  be considered beyond the national government's legitimate reach  under
the current interpretation of the Commerce Clause (its  constitutional authority
to regulate interstate commerce in order to  prevent the states from erecting
barriers against one another). He  was unable to provide a single example.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE COST OF RUNAWAY NATIONAL GOVERNMENT</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The central purpose of the Constitution was to ensure that  government
remained limited, but the system established to police  those limits has been
undone. As a direct result:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><CITE><B>-</B></CITE>     Government has expanded its reach
into all areas of American life;
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><CITE><B>-</B></CITE>     All major governmental decisionmaking has been
centralized  in Washington; and
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE></B>     A self-governing society has been replaced by
distant,  bureaucratic, and all-powerful government.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Advocates of the concentration of power in Washington  usually have pointed
to some pressing national need for action.  However, the costs associated with
these changes have rarely been  given more than passing consideration. The
centralization of power  in the hands of the national government has exacted a
heavy  economic price, weakened the democratic process, and helped to  undermine
civil society.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>I. The</B> <B>High Cost to Taxpayers</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Calculating the economic costs stemming from the demise of  federalism and
the expansion of the national government is  difficult, if only because of the
enormity of the task. These costs  include reduced economic growth for the
nation as a whole through  heavy taxation, burdensome regulation of businesses,
and the  skewed investment of resources.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     As programs have expanded to cover all areas of
national life,  the federal budget has grown commensurately, both in terms of 
taxpayer dollars and as a percentage of the national economy.  In 1934, the
national government accounted for 10 percent of  gross domestic product (GDP).
In 1948, it was still only 12 percent.  By 1960, however, it had ballooned to 18
percent, and by 1994, to  22 percent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The tax burden also has necessarily expanded. In 1914, the 
first year of the federal income tax, Americans making from $4,000  to $20,000
were taxed 1 percent of their incomes. The rate  gradually increased to 7
percent for Americans making over $500,000.  Because those making over $4,000 in
1914 accounted for less than  1 percent of the population, the average family
paid no income  tax. Even by 1950, following the expansion of the national 
government during and after the New Deal, the average American family  with two
children paid only 3 percent of its income to the federal  government. In 1994,
federal taxes accounted for 24 percent of a  typical family's income.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Though taxation has increased dramatically since World War 
II, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  spending has grown even faster. A
1991 study prepared for  the Joint Economic Committee found that for every $1
increase  in taxes since the end of World War II, expenditures have  grown
$1.59. The national debt now stands at $4.9 trillion,  representing more than
$18,500 for every man, woman, and child in the  country  an obligation that will
be paid by every individual and  family through higher taxes and lower living
standards.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Roughly one-third of the average family's income tax today  is
used merely to pay interest on the national debt, a significant  reduction in
standard of living for which that family receives no  benefits. Much of this
debt and tax burden is used to subsidize  special interests with political clout
in Washington, from millionaire  peanut farmers to the affluent elderly.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     By contrast, 49 of the 50 states are required to balance their
 budgets every year, making the perennial accumulation of debt  difficult if not
impossible. Although all opinion polls show that there  is overwhelming public
support for a balanced budget amendment  to the Constitution, every attempt to
have Congress pass the  measure has failed. Powerful special interests lobby
behind closed  doors against any proposal which would force Washington to cut 
spending, and the government continues to borrow money and  obligate future
generations for its repayment.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Overregulation</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>An enormous regulatory bureaucracy has been created in  Washington to
oversee every area of public and private life.  Although the public manifests
high levels of support for many  regulatory objectives, such as clean air and
water, access for the disabled,  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->  other social goals, one reason
for this popularity is that these  goals are commonly portrayed as having little
or no economic cost,  at least for the average citizen. The reach and
inflexibility of  the regulatory agencies lead to frequent absurdities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     The typical American business must sort through
and fill out  100 forms and booklets of information on how to comply with 
federal regulations.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;A Louisiana family applied for permits to build a
crawfish  pond on eighty acres of land it owned. The EPA denied permission 
stating `High quality habitats such as these provide food, shelter,  nesting and
spawning areas to a wide variety of game and  non-game fish...including the red
swamp  crawfish.'&quot;<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#2">2</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     &quot;Environmental and other regulations can increase
start-up  costs for a single dry cleaner as much as  $138,000.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#3">3</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     An Orange County development expected to inject $500  million
into the...local economy was halted when the Fish and  Wildlife Service placed
the Pacific Pocket Mouse on the endangered  species list. Before continuing the
project, regulators will have to  be convinced development will not harm the
mouse  population.<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#4">4</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The state of Arizona must regulate and monitor the Salt River 
to comply with fishing and swimming standards set by the Clean  Water Act of
1977, even though the river is dry 50 weeks of the year.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In 1991, a federal district judge found San Diego was not in 
compliance with certain Clean Water Act regulations dealing with  pretreatment
of sewage by industrial users and sewage spills in  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 -->  collection system. Instead of
confining himself to ordering the  city to rectify the noncompliance, the judge
mandated that the city  require the public at large to install smaller toilets
and  shower heads.<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#5">5</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Unfunded Mandates on the States</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unfunded federal mandates on state and local governments  are particularly
burdensome. The costs are substantial and fall not  just on state and local
governments, but also on private businesses  and individuals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Federal mandates are requirements laid down by  Washington, through
legislation, executive regulation or order, or judicial  fiat, which force state
and local governments to undertake certain  programs or provide certain services
at their own cost.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     The National Conference of State Legislatures
(NCSL) has  identified 192 unfunded mandates on the states, including  Medicaid,
regulations governing the use of underground storage tanks,  the Clean Water
Act, the Clean Air Act, the Resource  Conservation and Recovery Act, the Safe
Drinking Water Act, requirements  to remove lead paint and asbestos from schools
and other areas,  the Endangered Species Act, the Americans with Disabilities
Act,  and the Fair Labor Standards Act, to name only a few.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The U.S. Conference of Mayors and Price Waterhouse estimate 
the 1994-1998 cost of these mandates (excluding Medicaid) on  314 cities at $54
billion, or the equivalent of 11.7 percent of all  local taxes.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#6">6</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The EPA estimates that environmental mandates cost state  and
local governments $30 billion to $40 billion annually. Other  studies have
produced much higher numbers. The city of  Columbus, Ohio, estimates that it
will spend $1.3 billion from 1991 to 2001  to comply with EPA regulations; a
companion study estimates  that the annual cost of federal mandates to each
household in  Columbus will be $856 by the year 2000.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#7">7</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     State and local governments will spend an estimated $137 
billion to ensure safe drinking water under the Clean Water Act,  according to
the EPA.<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#8">8</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In 1991, the National School Board surveyed 670 school 
systems and revealed that the costs of complying with the Asbestos  Hazard
Emergency Response Act of 1986 had totaled $6 billion in the  five years since
the Act was passed. Estimates of the cost of full  compliance for all schools
reach $200 billion. These costs are  mandated in spite of mounting evidence that
asbestos removal  programs actually may increase the exposure of children to
asbestos.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Even though immigration is solely the responsibility of the 
national government, extensive judicial and legislative  mandates require states
and local governments to provide services to  illegal immigrants. The current
data are inconclusive on whether  illegal immigrants are a drain or benefit to
the economy as a whole,  but federal mandates that require the states to provide
 education, health services, and other services to illegal aliens still cost 
the states billions each year. The cost of incarcerating prisoners is 
especially burdensome. For the seven states most affected by  illegal
immigration (Arizona, California, Florida, Illinois, New  Jersey, New York, and
Texas), the Urban Institute estimates that,  even 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  after accounting for tax revenues
paid by working illegal  immigrants, net costs of services provided to illegal
aliens in 1992  alone totaled nearly $3 billion. And this is a low estimate. The
 California Office of Planning and Research estimated in 1994 that  illegal
aliens would cost the state a net $3.4 billion in FY  1994-1995.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#9">9</A> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P> In addition to unfunded mandates on the states, the federal  government
imposes costly requirements on states wishing to  receive money from federal
programs  money raised in the states  under the federal tax code.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Welfare</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Although a disproportionate share of federal spending has  produced adverse
results, it is in welfare that the greatest damage  may have been done. In
program after program, federal spending  not only has failed to solve the
problem, but actually has made  it worse. The economic costs alone from this
failure of social  planning are staggering.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     The most comprehensive analysis of government
welfare  spending puts the total over three decades at $5.4 trillion. In
addition to  this direct expenditure of taxpayers' dollars, the multiple 
generations of welfare dependency encouraged by these programs have  reduced
overall economic growth by removing recipients from  the productive economy,
along with the taxes they would have  paid.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#10">10</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>A squandering of resources on such an extraordinary scale  might be excused
if the programs produced positive results, but the  human and social costs of
this failed system easily exceed the  economic liabilities. These costs include
such things as  dramatically increased rates of crime, illegitimacy, and family
breakup,  all 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 -->  made possible or directly
produced by the current welfare  system. In the inner cities, where the numbers
of welfare recipients  are highest, the result usually has been economic and
social  devastation on a wide scale.<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#11">11</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Not only have federal programs not solved the problem of  poverty, but
Washington has actively prevented state and local  governments from
experimenting with new approaches. Efforts by  private and nonprofit groups,
especially religiously based groups  with excellent records of rehabilitation,
meet with countless  restrictions and discrimination and usually are shut out
altogether. Even  efforts by the poor themselves to reduce the power of federal 
bureaucrats and manage their own affairs have been blocked repeatedly  by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>II. The High Cost to Democracy</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>More difficult to calculate, but nevertheless far-reaching, are  the high
costs to democracy that stem from the demise of  federalism. An oft-repeated
description of the American system of  government is that it is a &quot;government
of laws, not of men,&quot; meaning that  the rules which govern society are
openly formulated, apply equally  to all, and are reliably stable over time.
Laws are made by  citizens and their elected representatives; they are not
supposed to be  subject to the whims of individuals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>However, this characterization is no longer accurate. Even as  federal power
over the economy, society, and all facets of  public policy has grown, the
concentration of decisionmaking in  Washington has radically reduced the ability
of the public to affect  it. Whereas the American people once were described
routinely  as 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 -->  self-governing and self-reliant,
it is now virtually impossible  for individuals or communities to influence the
decisions which  directly affect them. Distant rule-making bureaucracies are 
immune from local pressure; Congress is overrun with powerful and  well-heeled
interest groups; and enormous coalitions of citizens  are required to get even
rudimentary attention from Washington.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As local and state governments have been reduced increasingly  to the role
of implementing federal decisions, elections for them  have lost most of their
importance. Regardless of who holds office,  and regardless of the electorate's
intentions when electing these  officials, Washington need pay attention to none
of them as it  imposes programs on state and local governments. Governor Ben 
Nelson (D-NE) has said that he often feels he is merely an  administrator for
the federal government, and Governor Michael Leavitt  (R-UT) has noted that his
constituents, when referring to government,  now think almost exclusively in
terms of Washington, not state or  local government. National elections, in
turn, are not about  individual issues, but about large combinations of them,
with the  individual voter unable to register his preferences. And each voter's 
choice must compete with those of 100 million others. With their  votes meaning
so little in terms of how decisions are made, it is not  surprising that the
percentage of the electorate which goes to the  polls has declined steadily over
decades.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As the power of citizens has declined, however, that of  certain individuals
has grown. Committee chairmen in the House and  Senate, unelected staff, obscure
bureaucrats, and federal judges  wield vast powers which are often exercised out
of the public's  eye. Hundreds of bills with thousands of prescriptions,
allotments,  and prohibitions are passed each year, often with Members of  Con
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  gress having only the haziest of
ideas about their content. An  endless stream of special interests brings
enormous financial and  organizational capacities to bear on Congress and the
executive  branch  often to secure enactment of agendas these interests know 
the public would not support if given the opportunity to decide  for themselves.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Untethered Judiciary</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Even if elected officials could be made more responsive to  the public's
preferences, however, they would remain subject to  the unelected judges of the
federal courts. The Supreme Court and  the federal judiciary as a whole have
arrogated to themselves a  dominant role in every public and private institution
in society.  Federal judges have taken charge of wide areas of state and local 
jurisdiction and imposed on them their own dictates, from which there  is little
appeal. Individual judges overturn and rewrite laws,  suspend whole sections of
state constitutions, impose detailed  mandates, order actions by officials at
all levels, and even mandate the  imposition of taxes on populations which
refuse to vote for them.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>No area of American life can escape detailed examination and  reconstruction
by the Supreme Court. Members of the Court  are bound by little but their own
self-restraint. Cynics often say  that the Constitution is whatever the Supreme
Court says it is. In  fact, no less an authority than Chief Justice Charles
Evans  Hughes stated in a 1907 speech: &quot;We are under a Constitution, but 
the Constitution is what the judges say it is.&quot;  But the reality is  even
worse: It is whatever any five of the Court's nine justices say it  is. A 5 to 4
decision one day can be abruptly reversed the next;  what was once legal may
become illegal, and vice versa;  wrenching 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  changes can be produced by the
replacement of a single  individual on the Court, or even by a change of opinion
by any one of  the justices, regardless of the language of the Constitution or
the  preferences of the public.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Long-established rights may be cast aside, while newly  mined ones are put
in their place. No law, constitutional provision,  popular referendum, community
standard, or tradition, regardless of  its support among the people or their
elected officials, has any  meaning or standing other than that which the
federal courts choose  to give it. All may be set aside, and the public has no
recourse. It  is for this reason that the once-routine confirmations of  Supreme
Court justices have become brutal political contests.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     In 1972, the Supreme Court ruled that capital
punishment as  then practiced was &quot;cruel and unusual&quot; and thus
violated the  Eighth Amendment. This decision vacated death sentences of over 
600 inmates and overturned laws duly enacted by 39 state  legislatures elected
by the people. The Court said the death penalty was  &quot;offensive to
contemporary values,&quot; even though polls have  shown consistently that
Americans favor the death penalty by ratios of  up to 4 to 1. In 1976, the Court
reversed its decision, once again  allowing the death penalty, but only under
conditions it  unilaterally imposed and periodically revises. Even though
capital  punishment is specifically authorized in the Constitution, Justice 
Harry Blackmun publicly stated in 1993 that he would no longer vote  to allow
it.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Thirty-nine states and 300 of the nation's largest jails
operate  under some form of federal court direction. Federal court  orders cover
the administration of entire prison systems in nine  states 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 -->  down to such details as
supervising magazine subscription  lists, mandating the wattage of light bulbs,
and specifying the number  of basketballs, Ping-Pong tables, and pianos to be
kept on hand.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In 1995, after citizens in Kansas City voted to reject new 
property taxes to fund a desegregation plan imposed by a federal judge,  the
judge ordered the city to impose the taxes anyway. He was  overruled by an
appeals court on the grounds that other means  were available, but his authority
to impose the taxes was upheld.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Federal District Judge Norma Shapiro has taken over control 
of construction funds for Philadelphia's criminal justice system.  City
officials must present plans for new construction to the judge  for approval:
square footage and window locations in  administrative office spaces, the
position of the flag pole in the front of the  building, landscaping, and
similar plans  even for buildings that  house no prisoners.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In November 1995, a federal court struck down  California's
Proposition 187, which limited the rights of illegal immigrants  to free health,
welfare, and education benefits at the state's  expense and which had been
passed in November 1994 with  overwhelming public support. The judge ruled that
the state has no right to  limit benefits for illegal immigrants; nor can it
even question  applicants about their immigration status.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Also in November 1995, a federal judge in New York  City
blocked a fare increase by the New York Transit Authority,  saying that the
increase violated the U.S. Civil Rights Act because it  discriminated against
ethnic minorities who use the subway  system more heavily than the rest of the
public.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Voters today may vote on specific issues in referenda, may  approve changes
in their state constitutions or local  government charters, may elect
representatives to local and state  governments to accomplish specific tasks,
may repeatedly express their  preferences to their federal representatives, and
may go to court to  exercise their constitutional rights; in reality, however,
all they  really are doing is asking federal authorities beyond their control to
 notice their pleas and grant their requests. Unable to affect  decisions of the
national government, unable to exercise control over  their communities, the
American people have little option but to  wait for Washington's decisions.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>III. The High Costs to Civil Society</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Of all the costs produced by the demise of federalism, the  greatest have
been those associated with the breakdown of civil society:  the individuals,
families, communities, and voluntary  organizations and institutions which
together enable individuals to control  the environment in which they, their
families, and their  communities live and operate.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For the Framers, the purpose of government was to establish  and secure the
general environment within which civil society  could operate essentially
unmolested. Within this environment, the  array of social institutions would
regulate the public aspects of the  community and intrude in the lives of
individuals and families as  little as possible. Government, especially local
government  controlled by the adult citizenry, was essential to maintaining this
order,  but only if its power was limited to narrow purposes. It was well 
understood that the more distant the government, the less control  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 -->  citizens would have over its
actions, and thus the more damage  it could do.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Once the national government had freed itself from its  constitutional
restraints, however, its rapid expansion inevitably  undermined civil society,
because the purpose of expanded  government is to substitute itself for civil
society. The national government,  in centralizing power, inevitably has taken
control away from  citizens and communities and replaced it with  political
decisionmaking and bureaucratic administration. It also has  forcibly replaced
civil society's home-grown workings with its  own political and bureaucratic
vision of how society should be  structured and run, and with devastating costs.
Unconstrained  government and civil society cannot coexist; their respective 
resources are too unequal to permit competition. When government  expands,
society must retreat.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The result has been a broad decline in civilized life, especially  in the
nation's cities where government activism has been  greatest. Among the results:
vastly increased crime and violence, a  breakdown of public order, a decline in
community life, erosion of  the family, the rise of illegitimacy, and the
pervasive mediocrity  of public education, among other ills.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Social scientists profess bafflement at the emergence and  continuation of
these developments. Among the most common  explanations: America is an
inherently violent society, there has been  a &quot;war on the poor&quot;
stemming from hard-hearted budget cutters,  or endemic racism prevents progress.
The true source, however,  can be located directly in the engineered demise of
civil society and  its replacement by the federal government. Individuals,
families,  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 -->  communities have been stripped of
the ability to control  either their environment or the behavior of individuals
within it.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Rise in Crime</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The rate of violent crime in the U.S. has risen dramatically   over 400
percent since the late 1950s. Some of this is attributable to  the increase in
the population aged 15-30, the age group  responsible for the vast majority of
felonies. But if demographics were the  sole factor, the rate should have
plummeted in the 1980s along  with this segment's share of the population. It
did not, and other  countries with similar demographics did not experience the
same rise  in crime. Liberals claim the reason is widespread availability of 
guns in the United States, but gun ownership has been common in  the United
States since the country's inception. Moreover, other  societies, such as
peaceable Switzerland, that actually require all  able-bodied men to maintain
guns in their homes experience no  upsurge in drive-by shootings. Why, then, the
vast and rapid increase in  the rate of violent crime in the U.S. and its
continuance at such  high levels?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are two reasons. One is the breakdown in family structure  in America 
itself exacerbated by federal policies (see Chapter  6). The other is the
Supreme Court's radical reconstruction of  the criminal justice system in the
U.S., an all-embracing  exercise weighted consistently toward restricting the
policing power  of communities. Beginning in the 1960s, federal courts began 
viewing law enforcement, rather than criminals, as the principal  threat to
public safety and set out to restrict the power of police to  arrest criminals,
the ability of the judicial system to convict them,  and the right of society to
put and keep them behind bars. The  courts 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  vastly expanded, and even
invented, rights for criminals which,  if not actually written in the
Constitution, were held by the courts  to be &quot;inspired&quot; by its &quot;penumbras.&quot;
 However lofty this  solicitude for the rights of criminals may be, its
real-world impact has  been to create an America much more dangerous and violent
for  law-abiding citizens.<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#12">12</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To curb alleged coercion of defendants, the Supreme Court  has virtually
eliminated the ability of state and federal prosecutors  to use confessions by
the accused as evidence. In the mid-1960s,  with the Court's imposition of
arbitrarily detailed procedures for  arrest and investigation, the rate of
solved crimes plummeted  virtually overnight from the level of 70 percent in the
1950s to 40  percent, and hundreds of thousands of felons were never prosecuted 
even though ample evidence was available. In addition, severe  restrictions have
been placed on the collection of evidence; trials  increasingly focus not on the
defendant's innocence or guilt, but  on whether the police have adhered
sufficiently to procedural  minutiae.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     The famous warnings to suspects of their rights
grew out of a  Supreme Court case in 1966. Although Ernesto Miranda had 
confessed to the brutal rape of a woman in Arizona with &quot;full  knowledge of
my legal rights, understanding that any statement I  make may be used against
me,&quot; the Supreme Court ruled that the  police had failed to tell him he
could call a lawyer and ordered his  release from prison. Justice Thurgood
Marshall wrote that even an  indirect &quot;appeal to... ` decency and honor'
[was a] `classic  interrogation technique,'&quot; and thus  prohibited.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#13">13</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In 1980, a California man was acquitted after confessing he 
had 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 -->  beaten a female college student
to death. Although he  repeatedly had waived his right to see a lawyer, a
California appeals  court, following federal guidelines, found his confession 
inadmissible because he had not been allowed to speak with his  mother.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#14">14</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In 1983, the Justice Department estimated that up to 55,000 
serious criminal cases are dropped every year because  exclusionary rule
restrictions eliminate the evidence needed for prosecution.  By 1992, an
independent report concluded that the number had  grown to 120,000, including
30,000 violent crimes and 90,000  serious property crimes. This figure does not
include either the tens  of thousands of crimes that could have been prevented
or the  cases that never came to trial because police are effectively 
prohibited from gathering evidence and questioning suspects regarding  these
crimes.<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#15">15</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The results of these and many other innovations have been  nothing short of
disastrous: the release of criminals, plea-bargaining  down to less serious
charges, or  increasingly  no prosecution at  all. As the risk of punishment for
crimes of all types has been  reduced, so has the value of punishment as a
deterrent.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The death penalty was abolished by the Supreme Court in  1972, despite
widespread public support. Although partially reinstated  in 1976, it remains
exceedingly difficult to use, even when  requested by the convict himself.
Despite the Constitution's express  provisions for capital punishment, Justice
William Brennan stated  that he believed it to be unconstitutional and
prohibited &quot;under all  circumstances.&quot;<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#16">16</A>  A death penalty which everyone
knows  almost certainly will not be carried out is no deterrent.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The federal bench also has intervened to change the way  states deal with
felons convicted of crimes and sentenced to  prison terms. In state after state,
entire prison systems have been  taken over by the federal courts. Ostensibly to
eliminate  &quot;overcrowding,&quot; tens of thousands of prisoners have been
released onto  the streets. But &quot;overcrowding&quot; has never been
consistently  defined, so each judge is free to define it for himself on an
entirely  subjective basis. To several judges, therefore, it means not groups 
of prisoners crammed into single cells, but simply more than  one prisoner to a
cell, however large. Some federal judges even  refuse to allow convicted felons
to be sent to prison in the first place  because of &quot;overcrowding&quot; and
simply release them, even those  convicted of violent crimes and repeat
offenders. These released  felons have been responsible for tens of thousands of
additional  violent crimes.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>      In 1993, 20,350 criminals in Florida were
released early to  comply with a statewide population cap imposed by a federal
court.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In Cook County, Illinois, approximately 30,000 prisoners 
released each year from pre-trial detention under a prison population  cap
commit an additional 7,500 violent crimes  annually.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#17">17</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In 1981, a federal judge imposed a cap on the Texas prison 
population that forced the state parole board to increase early  prisoner
releases by over 400 percent. By 1986, there were more  convicted violent felons
on parole than behind bars, and those staying in  jail served only 60 days for
every year sentenced.<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#18">18</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Between 1983 and 1993, the state parole board in Georgia, 
operating under overcrowding restrictions imposed by the federal  court, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->  granted early release to 36,000
violent felons and sex  offenders (including 2,772 multiple sex offenders) who
had served an  average of 36 percent of their sentences.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>The Obsession with Prisoners' Rights </B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The federal courts have demonstrated an amazing solicitude  for the small
minority of felons who actually reach prison, being  especially attentive to
suits claiming violations of the  Eighth Amendment's prohibition of &quot;cruel
and unusual punishment.&quot;   To help prisoners develop and file these claims,
the federal  courts have ruled that prisoners must be provided with 
state-of-the-art law libraries in their prisons, and even with law clerks. 
Arizona Attorney General Grant Woods has said that the law libraries  in state
prisons are equipped with better services and resources  than those in his own
office.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As a result, the number of suits by prisoners claiming violations  of
constitutional rights has exploded in recent decades.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In 1966, prisoners brought 218 suits in federal court for  alleged
constitutional violations in state and federal prisons. In 1993,  prisoners
filed over 53,000 suits, primarily against state prisons,  representing 25
percent of all cases handled in federal courts and  7,000 more suits than the
federal government itself filed against  criminals. Most of this litigation is
frivolous  inmates have sued,  for example, because they were given creamy
instead of chunky  peanut butter, were denied breast implants at public expense,
or  did not like the color of their cells  and ultimately are dismissed  by the
courts. But the cost to the taxpayers is still heavy, as the  state must treat
each case seriously lest it be lost by default.  Generally, 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 29 -->  prisoners pay no fees, claiming
indigent status.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Keith Poladian, an inmate in New York's Auburn state  prison, brought suit
on Eighth Amendment grounds against the state's  use of razor wire on fences
used to contain prisoners, citing  possible injury to potential escapees. Of the
numerous federal suits filed  by him and other inmates, Poladian says, &quot;It
gives us a way to  be heard.&quot;<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#19">19</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>It is little wonder that most criminals show a psychology of  denial for
their criminal actions. Nevada Deputy Attorney General  Anne Cathcart says
criminals &quot;come into prison denying any  wrongdoing, and they are
constantly presented with further reasons  to blame others. Unlimited access to
federal courts gives them  an added tool to vent their anger and rebel against
the system.&quot;   But that is only one element. The total effect of the
federal courts  on the criminal justice system has been staggering. Thanks to a 
succession of messages to the potential felon  you won't be  arrested, you won't
be convicted, your sentence will be cut short,  prison isn't really so bad, and
your rights in prison are superior to  those of the administration, for example 
deterrence has been all  but destroyed. Even violent felons remain on the
streets, free to  commit crimes. Far from having a mysterious source, the 
enormous upsurge in crime was all but inevitable.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Under the guise of expanding individual rights, the federal  judiciary has
undermined the ability of communities and local  governments to maintain public
order.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     In 1991, a federal court in New York struck down
the  conviction of a woman who had thrown her feces at people as they passed 
her 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 30 -->  &quot;home&quot; on the sidewalk,
claiming that her First Amendment  right of free expression had been violated.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Richard Kreimer, a homeless man, spent his days at  the
Morristown, New Jersey, public library stalking, staring down,  and speaking
loudly and belligerently to library staff and patrons.  The library had a
regulation that said patrons could &quot;not annoy  others through noisy or
boisterous behavior.&quot;  With the help of  the American Civil Liberties
Union, Kreimer sued in federal court  in 1990. Federal Judge Lee Sarokin
overturned the regulation,  ruling that &quot;If we wish to shield our eyes and
noses from the  homeless, we should revoke their condition, not their library
cards....  [T]he cause of the revulsion may be of our own making.... [The 
library] cannot condition access on behavior, appearance, or hygiene  [because
it is] an unreasonable wealth classification.&quot;  This suit  ultimately cost
Morristown taxpayers $480,000. President Clinton  has appointed Judge Sarokin to
the U.S. Court of  Appeals.<A HREF="ftnt14.htm#20">20</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     In response to pleas from low-income parents
whose children  were being solicited by drug dealers, the Alexandria, Virginia, 
City Council in 1989 passed an anti-loitering statute aimed  specifically at
drug transactions. A federal court overturned the law the  following year,
saying it could be used against people &quot;distributing  campaign literature
and exchanging business cards.&quot;  Within a  year, the town had numerous
open-air drug markets, and  drug-related crimes had increased significantly.<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#21">21</A>
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>The streets of the nation's cities have become a permanent  home for tens of
thousands of individuals collectively labeled  &quot;the homeless.&quot;  But
this alleged lack of shelter is due not to the  hard-heartedness of budget
cutters, but to the fact that up to  three-
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 31 -->  fourths of America's homeless are
mentally ill or  drug-dependent and unable to care for themselves. The advent of
drugs in  the 1950s and 1960s led to the widespread closing of institutions 
that cared for the mentally ill on the assumption that drug therapy  had
eliminated most of the need for institutionalization. At the  same time, in
addition to destroying viable communities, federal  urban renewal projects
eliminated much of the housing space available  to the very poor. Much of this
lost housing has been replaced by  shelters and other facilities, but many of
these people refuse to live  in shelters, citing endemic violence, drug use, and
corruption,  and many more individuals are clearly incapable of making  rational
choices for themselves. Community efforts to bring the  homeless into shelters
have been blocked by the federal courts because  of alleged violations of civil
rights; freedom of assembly is  claimed by those permanently squatting in public
areas, and  panhandling has been granted First Amendment protection on grounds
of  freedom of expression.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE CLINTON ADMINISTRATION
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration has a mixed record, at best, in the  area of
reducing the power of the federal government and  devolving power back to the
states. Clinton has assisted states in  accelerating the waiver process whereby
state welfare and health care  agencies can receive exemptions from a host of
federal requirements as  they attempt novel approaches to welfare and health
care reforms.  Unfortunately, most governors are still frustrated at the slow 
granting of waivers by the Administration and many believe the entire  process
is flawed in that they are seeking exemptions from  federal 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 32 -->  laws they believe to be an
encroachment on state prerogatives.  For instance, the Clinton Administration's
proposal in 1994 to  revamp the nation's health care system envisioned a
diminishing role  for the states, which would merely administer a national
system  created and directed from Washington. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In areas such as environmental protection and federal  land-use policy, the
Clinton Administration has continued to support  a growing federal role and has
resisted attempts by the states to  devolve powers back to them. For instance,
this is most  evident among Western states, where Interior Secretary Bruce
Babbitt  has been promoting an overarching policy of environmental  protection
that dramatically increases the power of the federal government  in land-use
policy in federal, state-owned, and private lands. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To the extent the Administration has even focused on federalism  it has
missed the true meaning of the word. For instance, Vice  President Al Gore's
calls for a &quot;New Federalism&quot;are embodied in  his efforts to streamline
and reinvent the federal government  through its National Performance Review.
Regardless of the merits of  the National Performance Review  which attempts to
make the  federal government more efficient through downsizing and 
restructuring  it has had little if anything to do with reestablishing a 
balance between the state and federal governments. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>THE 104TH CONGRESS</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The 104th Congress has taken important first steps in the areas  of
devolution, federalism, and the restoration of constitutional  government. Under
the Contract With America, it passed  legislation that turns over most
responsibility for welfare to the states  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 33 -->  allows them more flexibility and
authority in the administration  of welfare programs. Even more important, it
has put the country  on course for a balanced budget in seven years. While not
strictly  an issue of federalism, bringing spending under control is a 
prerequisite both for reimposing limits on government's ambitions and  for
rebuilding civil society. The federal government also has agreed  to reimburse
the states for part of the education, health care,  and other costs associated
with the incarceration of illegal aliens.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In addition, a number of pending bills and resolutions are  designed to make
the federal government more responsive to its  constitutional limits. These
include requiring Congress to cite its  constitutional authority for each piece
of legislation, restricting the  ability of the federal judiciary to take over
state administrative  functions, and eliminating agencies of the federal
government which  exercise &quot;powers not delegated to the United States by
the  Constitution,&quot; among other proposals.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Correcting the many problems confronting American society  will involve more
than isolated reforms; a lasting solution will  require dealing with their root
causes, especially the federal  government's crushing impact on civil society.
This means more than  merely resurrecting the past. Too much has changed to
permit a  simple repeal of the many constitutional innovations of the preceding 
decades, and powerful and well-entrenched groups with  economic, political, and
ideological interests at stake are certain to resist  any change which
diminishes the power of Washington to reward  them from the public treasury and
impose their agendas on the rest  of 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 34 -->  the country. Instead, new
approaches must be developed that  draw on the lessons learned in this century
about Washington's ability  to free itself, Houdini-like, from almost any
constraint.
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Devolve power to the states by returning taxes, not
just programs.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Contract With America has taken the essential first step  in reversing
the trend toward centralization of power in  Washington by curtailing some
entitlements and allowing states greater  discretion over welfare and other
programs, but several additional  measures are needed to ensure its success.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Under current plans, the principal funding for programs  devolved to the
states will continue to be through block grants from  Washington. Although the
states gain flexibility, this formula  undermines accountability because the
federal government collects  the money but state and local governments spend it.
As a result,  the public is less able to connect the collection of taxes with
the  provision of services, and neither level of government has  sufficient
incentive to ensure that the money is spent wisely and frugally.  A far better
approach would be for Washington to bow out of  the picture entirely and return
the money to the people in the form of  a tax cut. The states could collect the
taxes themselves   and thereby assure a direct connection between taxes and
services   or allow individuals to retain the money for their own use. If this 
is not done, the likely consequence is that rising budgetary  pressures will
lead Washington simply to maintain current federal  requirements on the states
to deliver services while cutting back on  the federal grants to fund them.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The principal argument for continuing a federal role in these  programs is
that it assures equality of treatment for recipients,  regard
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 35 -->  less of whether they live in
high-income or low-income  states. This argument is based on a misunderstanding
of the actual  impact of federal spending. Federal funding for individual
programs  often does vary widely from state to state, but those variations 
largely disappear when a broader range of programs is considered.  For example,
if responsibility for the more than 70 programs that  comprise federal welfare
spending was turned over to the states  along with a broad reduction in the
federal income tax, only a few  states would be adversely affected, and none by
more than 5 percent  of current revenue. And this does not take into account
money  that states could save by providing services more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>It is also important for candidates to stress that devolution is  not
necessarily federalism. While state-friendly legislation passed  by Congress is
a marked improvement over past practice, the  current debate and decisionmaking
on devolution have been  conducted almost entirely from Washington's point of
view. The programs  to be transferred will continue to be subject to conditions
imposed  by the federal government, which can change them unilaterally at  its
discretion to suit its own needs. And Washington will retain  the ability to
reverse or modify its grant at any time. Devolution  is evidence not that
Washington has been restrained, but merely  that it has changed its mind.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Hold a constitutional convention on federalism.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Calling a convention to propose amendments to the Constitution  is the route
most favored by those who seek a quick and  comprehensive solution to the
problem of Washington's overreaching.  Two-thirds of the state legislatures may
call a constitutional  convention by petitioning Congress to do so, a provision
the Framers  included 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 36 -->  both to deny Congress a monopoly
on proposing amendments  and to prevent it from insulating itself from the
public will.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>In the two centuries since the Constitution's adoption, there  have been
several efforts to call a convention. The most notable  attempts in recent
decades include an effort in the 1960s to  overturn the Supreme Court's revision
of state constitutions regarding  the structure of state legislatures and
several efforts concerning a  balanced budget amendment, the most successful of
which reached  32 states by 1983.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The principal reason these and other efforts have not succeeded  is fear
that a &quot;runaway&quot; convention might lead to an extensive  rewriting of
the Constitution. But opponents generally do not  take into account the fact
that any amendment proposed by a  convention is exactly that: merely a proposal.
To become part of the  Constitution, it must be ratified by the same
three-fourths of the  state legislatures required for the approval of any
amendment put  forth by Congress.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Opponents also ignore the fact that, in effect, two permanent 
constitutional conventions already exist: Congress, which can  propose an
amendment on any subject at any time, and the Supreme  Court. Although the Court
technically has no role in the amending  process, its rulings repeatedly have
had the same effect, adding  and deleting sections as the justices see fit.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Opposing a convention called by the states merely ensures  that Congress and
the Supreme Court  and thus Washington   retain their monopoly on changing the
Constitution while denying  the states and citizens any real opportunity to
participate. This  position 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 37 -->  is understandable in those who
wish to keep power centralized  in Washington but somewhat perplexing when held
by  conservatives and others who profess a desire to restrict the federal 
government. Given the opposition, however, calls for a constitutional 
convention are not likely to be successful without considerable  public
education.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Revive the Tenth Amendment.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Efforts to revive the Tenth Amendment occupy a special place  in the
movement to restore federalism. The Tenth Amendment is  the &quot;federalism
amendment,&quot; a written contractual guarantee  against the expansion of
federal power. It has not performed as  intended because the political and other
mechanisms designed to make  it effective have been removed and because the
Supreme Court  has been allowed to render it null and void.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Indications that the Supreme Court may revive the Amendment,  at least in a
limited fashion, are easily exaggerated. In a  recent case,<A
HREF="ftnt14.htm#22">22</A> the Supreme Court made headlines
by ruling that the  states cannot always be used as simple administrative arms
of the  federal government. This was the first time in six decades that the 
Tenth Amendment had been used to restrict federal power, but even  this
vestigial application was decided by a very narrow majority (5  to 4) and can be
reversed at any time.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A grass-roots movement to revive the Tenth Amendment has  been gathering
strength. Several state legislatures have passed  resolutions stating their view
that the Amendment remains fully in  effect, with several going further to
demand that the federal  govern
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 38 -->  ment abide by its provisions.
However, this has occurred in  a largely uncoordinated and low-key manner, and
little  political pressure has been brought to bear on Washington.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Implement federalism legislation.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Though Congress has been an egregious violator of federalism,  it also has
the power to reverse its own excesses and curb those  of the executive and
judicial branches as well. The most  prominent effort in this regard is the
Contract With America's commitment  to returning to the states many functions
now performed by the  federal government, such as the primary responsibility for
 welfare. Efforts in other, more specific areas need to be made as well.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Unwilling to part with its own money, Congress often has  resorted to
requiring state and local governments to pay for programs  that Washington
enacts and for which it takes the credit. Faced with  a growing revolt in the
states because of the unsustainable  burden these mandates impose on state
budgets, Congress in 1994  passed the Unfunded Mandates Act, advertised as
largely solving  the problem. However, the scope of the Act is very limited, 
covering only new mandates while leaving the truly burdensome  existing ones in
place. More important, the legislation puts no real  restraints on Congress at
all, as it requires Congress merely to  label an unfunded mandate as such before
enactment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>As pressures on the federal budget increase, Congress may  be tempted to use
unfunded mandates to transfer responsibilities  for certain programs to the
states while keeping all or most of  the funding in Washington to balance the
federal books. States  and local communities need to close this gaping loophole
before  Con
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 39 -->  gress presents them with a <I>fait
accompli</I>.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Among the actions the next Congress should take:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     Restore constitutional authority.</B> At present,
Congress may  legislate on virtually any subject it chooses, regardless of  the
Constitution's actual provisions. Legislation sponsored by  Senator Spencer
Abraham (R-MI) and Representative John Shadegg  (R-AZ) seeks to restrict this
unlimited power by requiring that  each bill specifically cite Congress's
constitutional authority to act  in the affected area, including grants of
authority to the  executive branch. Although the bill might not prevent Congress
from  simply making up whatever constitutional authority seemed convenient  at
the time, the requirement that it do so publicly and on the  record might have a
restraining effect.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Curb the federal judiciary.</B> Article III of the Constitution 
gives Congress virtually unlimited power to regulate the federal  judiciary
through legislation; Congress should use this power to  limit the abuses of the
federal courts. Areas of possible  congressional action include, among others,
limiting the ability of federal  courts to force state and local governments
into burdensome and  open-ended consent decrees; restricting the ability of the
federal  courts to take over state and local administrative functions for
decades  at a time; directing that the measures federal courts impose to 
rectify problems at the state and local levels be appropriate to the  specific
situation; limiting the federal courts' appellate review power  in order to help
restore the autonomy of the individual states as  originally guaranteed by the
Constitution; and prohibiting courts  from ordering the imposition of taxes.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 40 --> 
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Propose constitutional amendments through Congress.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Since it is unlikely that a constitutional convention will be  called within
the next few years, Members of Congress should  propose several amendments that
can be presented to the states for  debate and ratification. The following are
among the measures needed  to restore a balance between the state and federal
governments:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     A balanced budget amendment.</B> The last proposal
for a  balanced budget amendment passed the House but failed by one vote  to
achieve the necessary two-thirds majority in the Senate. Passage  of such an
amendment must remain one of the highest priorities  for the 104th Congress or
its successors.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     A &quot;states' veto&quot; amendment.</B> There are several
versions of  amendments which would allow a majority of the state legislatures 
to veto or recommit federal legislation. Governor George Allen  (R-VA) has
proposed a measure that gives that power to a simple  majority of the state
legislatures; other versions would require  a supermajority or merely request
that Congress reconsider the  subject legislation or regulation. Restoring to
states the ability  to block the most objectionable national legislation would
help  reduce some of the blatant disregard for state and local interests  that
has characterized Washington for so long.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     An amendment to allow states to propose amendments.</B> Under  the
amending formulas of Article V, the states may not propose  constitutional
amendments except by calling a constitutional  convention. Since there are a
host of perceived and real dangers in calling  such a convention, this route has
proven unusable, and Congress  retains 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 41 -->  its monopoly on proposing
amendments to the Constitution.  However, amending Article V to allow the states
to propose  amendments without calling a convention, but subject to a 
congressional veto on such amendments, could overcome this obstacle.  Amendments
approved by Congress would be reintroduced in the  states for the three-fourths
approval needed to adopt an amendment  to the Constitution.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><CITE>-</CITE>     Support collective state action.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The principal factor in the demise of federalism and the growth  of
government in Washington is the undermining of the states'  ability to act as a
counterweight to the national government. The  states have been reduced to
subservience for so long that most have  lost the incentive to challenge
Washington and concentrate instead  on lobbying for better treatment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The principal problem confronting the states is fragmentation: 
Individually, states cannot have much influence in Washington;  only by
combining their efforts can they bring to bear the political  pressure needed to
deal with Washington as equals.  Unfortunately, however, the existing
organizations that serve state officials,  such as the National Governors'
Association (NGA), have not  succeeded in promoting an independent and effective
voice.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A number of efforts in this area have been made in recent  years, the most
notable being the Conference of the States. Initiated  by Governors Mike Leavitt
(R-UT) and Ben Nelson (D-NE) in  1994 and joined by the NGA and other
organizations, along with  scores of state officials, the COS was designed to
create a process  by which the states could meet, discuss their common problems 
and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 42 -->  recommended solutions, and bring
their collective influence  to bear on Washington.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For many reasons, the COS was not able to achieve the goals  it laid out for
itself, but some similar effort would prove to be  invaluable to the states in
their dealings with Washington.  Among the possible steps:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*     Suits against the federal government.</B> Several
states have  initiated or are contemplating suits against the federal government
 for abuse of its authority, especially on Tenth Amendment  grounds. Arizona
leads this effort; the legislature voted in 1994 to  establish a Constitutional
Defense Council and appropriated $1 million  for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Mandates recall.</B> Beginning with Alabama in 1992, a number  of
state legislatures have established annual meetings between  themselves and
members of their congressional delegations to  review the latter's votes on
unfunded federal mandates. Although  the states cannot compel attendance or
attentiveness, there is a  certain political cost for those who simply ignore
such requests, and  the meetings do provide a way for both sides to air their 
respective concerns.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>Far more should be done to reconnect the state legislatures to  the making
of national policy. It once was common for state  legislatures to instruct their
representatives in Washington on how to  vote on particular issues, even if the
latter chose to ignore them.  On issues which affect a state, its legislature
certainly has at least  as much claim to represent the interests of the people
as does  any federal representative, and it should not hesitate to make its 
views 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 43 -->  known.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Term limits.</B> An additional area for emphasis is imposing  term
limits on federal officials, the theory being that a guaranteed  turnover will
reduce the opportunities for elected officials to  insulate themselves from the
voters and guarantee a continuing infusion  of individuals who are closer to the
people. Term limits by  themselves, however, will neither constrain Washington's
power  nor erect a permanent barrier to activism, even on the part of 
short-termers. More important, the Supreme Court has ruled that  the people have
no right to impose term limits on federal officials,  and proponents are now
seeking other ways  including a  constitutional amendment  to advance this
objective.(See table below)
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Some actions being taken by states and citizens to limit  federal power and
reassert state sovereignty:
</P>
<TABLE><TR><TD COLSTART="1"><B>Action</B></TD><TD COLSTART="2"><B>Selected States Involved</B></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">State suits against the
federal government would  force repayment of hundreds of millions of dollars
incurred by  mandatory expenditures on health care, education, and incarceration
 of illegal aliens. </TD><TD COLSTART="2"><B>Arizona, California, Florida,
Texas</B></TD></TR><TR><TD COLSTART="1">Challenges to the National Voter
Registration Act  that requires state motor vehicle departments to register
voters and  provide other voter services.</TD><TD COLSTART="2"><B>California, Pennsylvania, South  Carolina, Virginia</B></TD></TR>
