Stevens
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q&amp;A</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 48 --> 
</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q.What is the difference between devolution and federalism  and can they
contradict one another?  
</B></P>
<P><B>A.</B> Devolution legislation in Congress has dealt primarily  with
granting greater flexibility and decision-making authority to  state and local
governments in specific programs such as welfare.  Federalism, in contrast, is
concerned with the structure of  government as a whole and deals with the proper
balance that should exist  between the state governments and the national
government as  outlined in the U.S. Constitution. Current efforts to devolve 
selected powers from Washington to the states, however beneficial,  will have
only a small impact on the balance of power between  the federal and state
governments; Washington's primacy will  remain largely unaltered. For example,
the debate and  decision-making regarding devolution have been almost entirely
the product of  the Congress; state and local officials have played only 
secondary roles. As a result, the design and extent of the affected  programs
reflect Washington's preferences far more than those of the  states, and even
the devolved responsibilities remain subject to  unilateral revision by the
federal government. Devolution concerns the  reapportioning between the federal
and state governments of the  responsibility for current programs; federalism
addresses the  means by which Washington and the states can be made to limit 
each other's power.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Are there issues too important to entrust to state governments?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The domination of the national government by the states  under
the Articles of Confederation produced such chaos that the  Framers of the
Constitution sought to permanently redress the  balance. As a result, the
Constitution lists several powers reserved to  the national government and makes
its laws superior to those of  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 49 -->  states in these areas. That grant
of power, however, is strictly  limited. The Constitution specifies procedures
for amending the  document to alter that list should a sufficient majority of
the  country desire it, but it does not sanction federal action simply because 
it may be efficient or expedient. Under the system established by  the Founders,
state governments and the national government were  to have distinct and limited
powers in order to serve as a check  on one another.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The presumption throughout much of this century, however,  has been that the
national government is progressive and the  states regressive, and therefore
that progress requires a centralization  of power in Washington. Once achieved,
however, the result has  been not only to shift most decision-making to the
federal  government, but to make possible the vast expansion of government 
throughout every area of society, with decidedly negative results.  Whatever the
past failings of the states, they pale in comparison with  those of the federal
government. Federalism is not based on the  assumption that one level of
government is necessarily better than  another; instead, it holds that limited,
constitutional government  is the goal and that the different levels are needed
to restrain  one another.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Q. If states assume more power under a reinvigorated  federalism, how will
civil rights be protected?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A. A reinvigorated federalism would not reduce the power of  the federal
government to protect the civil rights guaranteed by  the Constitution. The Bill
of Rights, and especially the Fourteenth  and Fifteenth Amendments, provide the
federal government with  sufficient powers to enforce the civil rights of all
Americans. In  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 50 -->  past, the political will to
exercise these powers was often  lacking, a failing which has been more than
made up for over the past  four decades. Nevertheless, advocates of an activist
federal  judiciary often cite the need for an unelected protector of civil
rights  to guard minorities against the inevitable abuses of the  majority.
However, the contempt for the citizenry this attitude is based on  is wholly
contradictory to the theory of the American  government &quot;which rests on the
consent of the governed.&quot;  The  assumption must be that the majority wants
the rights of minorities (of  which everyone is a member of at least one) to be
fully guaranteed,  and for this reason has brought into being a Constitution
which has  that objective as one its principal goals. To assume that the purpose
 of government is to override and suppress the desires of a  thuggish and
intolerant majority is to believe that self-government is  an impossibility.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Q. Isn't the U.S. economy becoming so sophisticated that a  national
economic and regulatory regime is needed to maintain  competition in the global
economy? 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>A. Taken to its logical conclusion, this approach would argue  for the
superiority of international regulation over national  regulation. However, one
of the most important phenomena of the last  quarter of the 20th century is the
widespread realization that the costs  of governmental control over the economy
greatly exceed its  benefits. Communist economies have collapsed; socialist and 
heavily regulated economies have stagnated; and free-market  economies
increasingly have demonstrated the benefits of reducing the role  of the state
through such measures as privatization and the  lowering of trade barriers.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 51 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To this has been added the new pressures and opportunities of  the emerging
global economy, which is rapidly undermining the  idea of separate national
economies. This new economy places an  emphasis on flexibility and the ability
to adapt quickly to  changing economic and commercial realities. Slumbering
central  governments are proving to be grossly inadequate to such a challenge. 
A renewal of federalism would not replace Washington's  regulation with that of
the states as much as it would allow the latter to  experiment with policies
that are more conducive to  economic growth. Every state would have an interest
in promoting its  own economic growth, and competition between them would 
ensure that only the most beneficial policies survived. The federal  government
would continue to exercise its crucial function of  preventing the states from
erecting their own barriers against one another.  The overall limitations on
government at all levels that this  system would encourage would ensure a more
positive environment  for economic growth.
</P>
<P>

<P><center><B><A HREF="chpt13.html">Previous Chapter</A> | <A HREF="forintro.html">Next Chapter</A> | <A HREF="tblcon.html">Table of Contents</A> | <a href="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a> </B>
</center>

<p>
</BODY></HTML>
